but I was sitting

01:11.407 --> 01:13.341
Next to alan cummings,
and I got scared.

01:13.409 --> 01:14.743
Whatever. Hayley,
you're up.

01:14.810 --> 01:16.311
So, I think
I finally figured out

01:16.379 --> 01:18.046
Why you never want
to talk to me.

01:18.114 --> 01:19.381
Next. Somebody
go next.

01:19.448 --> 01:21.316
Dad, you know how I've
been working really hard

01:21.384 --> 01:23.952
With my a cappella group,
here comes treble?
Hmm.

01:24.019 --> 01:27.188
My music teacher selected me
to sing the national anthem

01:27.256 --> 01:29.791
At the langley falls
veterans day celebration!

01:29.859 --> 01:31.393
That's fantastic!

01:31.460 --> 01:34.562
My boy singing the
greatest song ever written

01:34.630 --> 01:38.133
To the greatest men ever
made: American soldiers.

01:38.200 --> 01:39.401
Steve, serenade me.

01:39.468 --> 01:40.769
(clears throat)

01:40.836 --> 01:42.871
(soulfully):
¶ oh-ho, ho ¶

01:42.938 --> 01:45.407
¶ say, can you ¶

01:45.474 --> 01:48.843
¶ see-hee-hee-hee, hee... ¶

01:48.911 --> 01:50.412
Steven, what the hell?

01:50.479 --> 01:52.213
<i>Did you just watch
the wiz or something?</i>

01:52.281 --> 01:54.315
I'm just putting
some personal flavor on it.

01:54.383 --> 01:55.884
Just sing it like
a normal person.

01:55.951 --> 01:57.886
¶ oh, oh, say-- ¶

01:57.953 --> 01:59.120
Okay, got it--
still sucks.

01:59.188 --> 02:00.755
I thought it was great.

02:00.823 --> 02:03.224
Have you been standing
there the whole time?

02:03.292 --> 02:04.926
That's weird.

02:04.994 --> 02:06.594
I had no idea
you were there.

02:09.330 --> 02:11.099
Anyway, steve,
it's fine,

02:11.167 --> 02:13.668
But not nearly good enough
for the ears of veterans.

02:13.736 --> 02:15.570
Tell you what, I'll take
the next couple days

02:15.638 --> 02:17.672
Off work, and we'll get
that song just right.

02:17.740 --> 02:18.773
Thanks, dad.

02:18.841 --> 02:20.175
I don't want
to mess this up.

02:20.242 --> 02:21.943
No, you really don't.

02:22.011 --> 02:24.679
Now, go upstairs and line
your throat with vaseline.

02:24.747 --> 02:26.147
Makes your voice
come out smoother.

02:26.215 --> 02:28.082
It's an old
elton john trick.

02:28.150 --> 02:29.951
(whistling joyfully)

02:32.188 --> 02:36.558
(bird twittering tune)

02:36.625 --> 02:40.728
(both whistling tune)

02:40.796 --> 02:42.697
(twittering tune)

02:42.765 --> 02:43.832
(gasps and groans)

02:43.899 --> 02:45.300
Annoying!
Both of you.

02:45.367 --> 02:46.701
I love your new pet.

02:46.769 --> 02:48.002
It's not a pet, silly.

02:48.070 --> 02:49.337
It's my meal for
the big night.

02:49.405 --> 02:50.405
(gasps) roger!

02:50.473 --> 02:52.507
You can't kill
this sweet bird.

02:52.575 --> 02:54.242
It's an ortolan, francine--

02:54.310 --> 02:56.177
The ultimate french delicacy.

02:56.245 --> 02:58.546
It so sinfully decadent
that you eat it

02:58.614 --> 03:01.316
Under a napkin
to hide your sin from god.

03:01.383 --> 03:03.384
And I only trust
you to cook it.

03:03.452 --> 03:04.419
(gasps)

03:04.487 --> 03:05.753
I'm honored.

03:05.821 --> 03:06.855
Here's the recipe.

03:06.922 --> 03:08.423
You actually drown
it in amaretto,

03:08.491 --> 03:10.458
Then save its life
using bird cpr,

03:10.526 --> 03:12.026
Then refill the pot
with crème de menthe

03:12.094 --> 03:13.428
And drown it again.

03:13.496 --> 03:15.396
There is something so sweet
about your hair today.

03:15.464 --> 03:16.598
I love it.

03:16.665 --> 03:18.299
Thank you.

03:18.367 --> 03:22.136
¶ by the dawn's
early light... ¶

03:22.204 --> 03:23.771
Stop. Take a break.

03:23.839 --> 03:25.640
I got to shake my head
in disappointment

03:25.708 --> 03:26.708
For five minutes.

03:28.310 --> 03:30.712
<i>So, stan, I tried to order
barbra does celine</i>

03:30.779 --> 03:32.180
On pay-per-view,
but it was locked.

03:32.248 --> 03:33.314
I need the code.

03:33.382 --> 03:34.549
How much is it?
It's priceless,

03:34.617 --> 03:36.384
But to order it,
it's four ninety-nine.

03:36.452 --> 03:38.853
I guess we can add
five more bucks to your tab.

03:38.921 --> 03:40.154
(laughing):
Five dollars?

03:40.222 --> 03:41.523
<i>For barbra does celine?</i>

03:41.590 --> 03:42.624
No!

03:42.691 --> 03:44.659
Oh, no, ridiculous.

03:44.727 --> 03:46.828
No, four hundred
and ninety-nine dollars.

03:46.896 --> 03:49.264
Streisand comes expensive
or she doesn't come at all.

03:49.331 --> 03:50.798
Forget it!

03:50.866 --> 03:52.867
<i>I wouldn't pay that much
to see barbra do celine.</i>

03:52.935 --> 03:54.135
Or would I?

03:54.203 --> 03:55.870
Maybe if I was in the room
with them,

03:55.938 --> 03:57.071
Peeking from behind the curtain,

03:57.139 --> 03:58.840
And they didn't know
I was there.

03:58.908 --> 04:00.875
How would it appear
on my credit card bill?

04:00.943 --> 04:02.176
No, no, stan, focus.

04:02.244 --> 04:03.411
Here's the deal.

04:03.479 --> 04:05.513
You and I both know
I'm going to get

04:05.581 --> 04:07.749
That pay-per-view code
one way or another,

04:07.816 --> 04:10.084
So you might as well
just give it to me now

04:10.152 --> 04:12.220
And avoid happy hour
at shenanigans.

04:12.288 --> 04:13.788
No.
Fine.

04:13.856 --> 04:15.089
Let it begin.

04:15.157 --> 04:17.058
Crab walk!

04:17.125 --> 04:18.860
Should've played ball.

04:20.396 --> 04:23.264
Steve:
¶ the rockets' red glare ¶

04:23.332 --> 04:24.332
No!

04:24.400 --> 04:26.034
I've been in the shower
all night.

04:26.101 --> 04:27.735
Yeah, I don't get it--
I thought people

04:27.803 --> 04:29.370
Were supposed to sing
better in the shower.

04:29.438 --> 04:30.471
I don't know.

04:30.539 --> 04:31.806
Maybe the problem
isn't you.

04:31.874 --> 04:34.642
Maybe... Maybe I'm not
a great vocal coach.

04:34.710 --> 04:36.010
God, could that be?

04:36.078 --> 04:37.612
No, dad, it's me.

04:37.680 --> 04:39.414
I just need
to sing harder.

04:39.481 --> 04:40.848
No, it's more
than that.

04:40.916 --> 04:42.250
There something
missing,

04:42.318 --> 04:45.253
Something empty and soulless
about your performance.

04:45.321 --> 04:46.688
Hmm.

04:46.755 --> 04:48.022
(snaps fingers)
that's it.

04:48.090 --> 04:50.458
See, steve, the national
anthem is about war,

04:50.526 --> 04:52.093
And you'll never
be able to sing it

04:52.161 --> 04:53.661
Until you've
been to war.

04:53.729 --> 04:55.096
Can you expand
on that idea?

04:55.164 --> 04:56.297
Certainly.

04:56.365 --> 04:57.832
Take the song,
"love in a elevator."

04:57.900 --> 04:59.133
The reason
it's so good

04:59.201 --> 05:00.802
Is because steven
tyler actually lived

05:00.869 --> 05:02.503
In an elevator the
summer he wrote it.

05:02.571 --> 05:04.205
<i>But the song's called
"love in an elevator",</i>

05:04.273 --> 05:05.607
<i>Not "live
in an elevator".</i>

05:05.674 --> 05:08.009
Steve, he's a rock star
living in kick-ass elevator.

05:08.077 --> 05:09.310
You don't think
he's getting laid?

05:09.378 --> 05:11.245
Oh, and it's
summertime.

05:13.882 --> 05:15.383
Some of my
nra buddies

05:15.451 --> 05:17.118
Rent this golf
course once a month.

05:17.186 --> 05:18.953
Since you can't
go to a real war,

05:19.021 --> 05:20.788
A reenactment is the
next best thing.

05:20.856 --> 05:23.424
I've always wanted to go
to a civil war reenactment.

05:23.492 --> 05:24.959
It's not a civil
war reenactment.

05:25.027 --> 05:26.294
Those things are
for historians

05:26.362 --> 05:27.595
And people who
hate blacks.

05:27.663 --> 05:29.797
These guys are
hardcore reenactors.

05:29.865 --> 05:31.432
(heavy gunfire)

05:31.500 --> 05:33.334
(explosions and gunfire)

05:36.138 --> 05:37.538
(groans)

05:37.606 --> 05:39.073
Get down!

05:39.141 --> 05:40.074
(explosion)

05:40.142 --> 05:41.843
(screams) where are we?

05:41.910 --> 05:43.645
You in vietnam, bitches!

06:10.042 --> 06:12.477
We're reenacting
the vietnam war?

06:12.545 --> 06:15.079
This chopper will take
you to base camp.

06:15.147 --> 06:16.748
(man imitating whirring
helicopter blades)

06:16.815 --> 06:17.982
Get in!

06:18.050 --> 06:19.317
(continues imitating helicopter)

06:19.385 --> 06:21.219
(gunfire)

06:22.621 --> 06:23.655
(screams)

06:28.794 --> 06:30.361
Platoon, gather round!

06:31.830 --> 06:33.565
The vietcong may be making
their move tonight.

06:33.632 --> 06:34.866
We need a watchman.

06:34.934 --> 06:36.601
Dad.
Steve will do it.

06:36.669 --> 06:38.836
We're counting on
you tonight, steve!

06:38.904 --> 06:40.838
Here, I'll even loan
you my lucky machete.

06:40.906 --> 06:42.240
A permanent marker?

06:42.308 --> 06:43.741
Use it like a knife.

06:43.809 --> 06:47.812
Leave the blade in the sheath
so it doesn't get dull.

06:47.880 --> 06:50.014
Leave the cap on so
it doesn't dry out.
(whispering):

06:53.319 --> 06:56.120
Dad, I don't know if I
can stand watch all night.

06:56.188 --> 06:58.590
You've kept me up for the past
two days practicing singing.

06:58.657 --> 07:01.426
Steve, this is an opportunity
to step up and be a hero.

07:01.493 --> 07:02.727
Then, you'll know
what it takes

07:02.795 --> 07:04.529
To really sing
our national anthem.

07:04.597 --> 07:06.364
Radio me if you
have any problems.

07:06.432 --> 07:07.632
I'll do my best, dad.

07:07.700 --> 07:09.434
I want more
than your best, steve.

07:09.501 --> 07:12.537
For once, I want you
to do fine.

07:14.707 --> 07:19.444
